@NoahHaber @github @Bioconductor This also relates to another realization I’ve had programming in #rstats over 20 years. Minimize dependencies. There is so much already built in to base R efficiently and robustly that when building a package it pays for the author to spend a little extra time to use them 2/3

@llisonwndrland @dvaughan32 There is extensive base #rstats support for dates. #lubridate makes things easier and more #tidyverse-ish, but (as a broken record) I maintain package creators/maintainers should minimize dependencies. Package USERS should do what ever works best for them.

@J_D_Klein @NoahHaber Almost anything lubridate does can be done in base #rstats. Yes, interactivity will be more cumbersome, but I think it’s in package developers best interests to minimize dependencies.

#Rstats users, please select how you use the #tidyverse in your general R usage. Please retweet for a larger sample. @topepos indicated that there will not be much development on #caret and focus is on #tidymodels so I’d like to get a feel. Yes, Twitter isn’t a great sample 🤓

@NoahHaber That is the nature of the ecosystem. To be part of #CRAN you accept the rules of Ripley et al as regards #rstats packages. You can disseminate through @github or @Bioconductor as alternative channels. I for one appreciate CRAN’s efforts in keeping R rock-solid and stable 1/2

#rstats tip: Example of how factors are useful

If x is a long character vector with many duplicate entries and you want to perform character manipulation, then, for example

x <- factor(x)
levels(x) <- tolower(levels(x))
x <- as.character(x)

is much faster than

x <- tolower(x)
